keep.name: Quassy Amusement Park
keep.description: Quassy is a great little amusement park in Central Connecticut, just off I-84. It has some nice old roller coasters, a great carousel, swimming and paddle-boating, and some classic arcade games. In addition to one or two new photobooths, they've still held onto this one, a black and white machine that turns out some nice photos, fairly dark but full of character. **UPDATE** 6/1/17: I can confirm after visiting the park that the photochemical booth is no longer here, though the nice "PHOTOS" sign still hangs in the arcade window.

keep.name: Skylon III
keep.description: This nice-looking photobooth, whose model and serial number plate had been removed, sits next to the 'Over the Falls in a Barrel' photo-stand on the first level of the Skylon Tower. We had no luck getting it to work, though the woman who worked at the photo stand seemed to think it had been working, and tried plugging a few cords in for us, which was nice of her. No luck, though, so we left the place empty handed. UPDATE 4/22/15: Thanks to Katie for submitting a sample photo, taken with her boyfriend, now husband, in this booth on June 4, 2004. UPDATE 12/17/21: Rebecca contacted the Skylon about their booths, and received the following response: 'Sadly, we no longer have a photobooth located on our premises. It has been removed.' Contributed by Brian, Katie Peek, Rebecca.

keep.name: Reel Bar
keep.description: This recent addition to the Boston bar scene was pretty quiet the night we stopped by, but looked like it could get pretty busy, with live music and DJs every night. We played a few rounds of Galaga and Pole Position with a remote control joystick and a TV over the bar. The photobooth is located in the front window, just to the left of the door, and produces nice looking black and white photos, with a little bit of brown staining the night we used it. The booth, a Photo-Me 21T, is $3, and seems to have every one of the bar's permits and licenses slipped into the front display. **UPDATE** 11/19/08: According to Jille, The Reel Bar is now a bar called Deep Ellum, and the photobooth is no longer located there.

merged.description: This is the only black and white chemical photobooth left in Toronto. It is serviced by Auto-Photo Canada but has been customized for Steam Whistle. The sample pictures along the booth feature people playing a drinking game where they have to drink a pint of beer over the four photos. There is a large vinyl sticker with the brewery's logo as the background (though you can choose to cover this with the curtain). Otherwise it runs normally and is serviced semi-regularly. Our photos turned out quite dark, but I've seen others from this booth that are more normal. UPDATE April 21, 2013: Emily writes that 'I was...informed by staff that the booth has been removed, because of its unreliability on event rentals of the location. So they ditched it a few months ago. Sad fact: it took too much energy to maintain it to be worth their time.' Contributed by Meags Fitzgerald, Emily Brown.
